# YuktiCastle agent orchestration env vars.
# Copy to .yukticastle/.env and fill in. Never committed (.gitignore).

# ─── Anthropic auth — pick ONE. Detection order (first hit wins): ───
#
#   1. macOS Keychain OAuth (entry: "Claude Code-credentials")
#      Best on macOS. Free via MAX subscription. Auto-refreshes when
#      operator runs `claude` on the host. Set up once:
#        claude  # sign in interactively (Enter once, then Ctrl+C)
#      No env var needed here — main.mts reads the Keychain directly.
#
#   2. CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN — long-lived OAuth (sk-ant-oat01-...)
#      Best on Linux / GitHub Codespaces / any non-Mac host. Free via
#      MAX subscription. Mint with `claude setup-token` (the CLI prints
#      the token once — right-click-copy from terminal, don't transcribe
#      by hand; tokens are ~120 chars including easily-misread I/Z, 5/S,
#      B/8, and may wrap across two visual lines).
#
#   3. ANTHROPIC_API_KEY — per-token billed (sk-ant-api03-...). ~$0.20-
#      0.30 per typical 4-commit agent run. No MAX involvement; works
#      identically on any host.
#
#   4. macOS Keychain API key (entry: "yukticastle-anthropic-api-key").
#      Stored once via `npm run yukticastle:api-key:set`. Same billing
#      as #3, less per-project paste-the-key toil. macOS-only.
#
# Project-local values here always win over Keychain entries.
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=
CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN=

# ─── "Never accidentally pay extra" guard ───
#
# When the operator has a Claude MAX or Business subscription, every
# run should draw from that quota — not from per-token API billing.
# Set YUKTICASTLE_REQUIRE_OAUTH=true to make main.mts REFUSE to start
# if neither OAuth backend (#1 Keychain, #2 CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN
# above) is available. Better to fail fast than to silently API-key-
# bill a run the operator thought was free.
#
# Recommended for any subscriber: set this once and forget it. The
# only downside is that runs require the operator to keep OAuth fresh
# (re-mint token on Codespace rebuild, run `claude` periodically on
# macOS to refresh the Keychain entry).
#
# Backward-compat: SANDCASTLE_REQUIRE_OAUTH (legacy) is also honored.
# YUKTICASTLE_REQUIRE_OAUTH=true

# ─── OpenAI / Codex — needed when REVIEWER=codex (toggle below). ───
#
# Two auth paths. The model/auth matrix below was empirically verified
# 2026-05-15 (earlier docs had it backwards):
#
#   Model name                              ChatGPT OAuth   OPENAI_API_KEY
#   ─────────────────────────────────────  ─────────────   ──────────────
#   gpt-5, gpt-5-mini, o4-mini, …                ✓ free         ✓ paid
#   gpt-5-codex, gpt-4-codex (-codex suffix)     ✗ rejected     ✓ paid
#
# So if you have a ChatGPT subscription (Plus/Team/Pro/Business) and
# want free reviewer runs, use `gpt-5` or similar non-codex model.
# The `-codex` suffix variants are PAID-API-ONLY — OpenAI's API
# explicitly rejects them for ChatGPT-account auth with:
#   "The 'gpt-5-codex' model is not supported when using Codex with
#    a ChatGPT account."
#
# Setup:
#
#   A. Free via ChatGPT subscription (recommended if you have one):
#      Run `codex login` on the host once (interactive — opens
#      browser). Creates `~/.codex/auth.json`. main.mts forwards
#      it into the reviewer container automatically. Use a non-codex
#      model in roles.json (e.g. `"model": "gpt-5"`). No env var.
#      Refresh anytime with `npm run codex:login`.
#
#   B. Paid via API key (works for any model including -codex):
#      Set OPENAI_API_KEY below (sk-…). ~$0.05–0.30 per reviewer
#      phase depending on diff size + model.
#
# Both paths can coexist; the codex CLI picks per-call based on the
# model name + which auth is available.
OPENAI_API_KEY=

# Reviewer agent selection (default: claude).
#   REVIEWER=claude  — claude-sonnet-4-6, same family as implementer.
#                      Free via Claude MAX/Business. Fast, cheap,
#                      catches the obvious stuff. Good default.
#   REVIEWER=codex   — GPT-5 family via Codex CLI. Different family →
#                      catches things Claude rationalized away. Use
#                      for schema migrations, security-sensitive code,
#                      anywhere an independent perspective matters.
#                      Two cost paths (see OPENAI section above):
#                      - Free: roles.json `model: "gpt-5"` (or any
#                        non-`-codex` model) + ChatGPT subscription
#                        + `codex login` on host
#                      - Paid: roles.json `model: "gpt-5-codex"` (or
#                        anything) + OPENAI_API_KEY above
# REVIEWER=claude

# ─── Codex access_token auto-refresh (PR #48) ───
#
# Codex access_tokens have ~1h life vs claude's ~6h. When the host's
# `~/.codex/auth.json` access_token is stale at run-start, main.mts
# pings `codex exec --model <REVIEWER_MODEL> ok` on the host to
# trigger a refresh-and-writeback BEFORE forwarding auth.json into
# the reviewer container. Eliminates the "every morning the first
# YC run 401s" pattern caused by overnight token staleness (the
# container can't write refreshed tokens back to the host, so
# pre-PR-#48 the host stayed stale forever).
#
# Defaults are sensible; override only if you have a reason.
#
# YUKTICASTLE_CODEX_OAUTH_MIN_REMAINING_MS (default: 900000 = 15 min)
#   Triggers the refresh when the access_token's `exp` claim is
#   within this many ms of now.
# YUKTICASTLE_CODEX_OAUTH_MIN_REMAINING_MS=900000
#
# YUKTICASTLE_CODEX_AUTO_REFRESH (default: true)
#   Set to "false" to disable the host-side refresh entirely
#   (reverts to pre-PR-#48 behavior: container's CLI tries to
#   refresh but the new token dies with the container).
# YUKTICASTLE_CODEX_AUTO_REFRESH=true
#
# YUKTICASTLE_CODEX_REFRESH_MODEL (default: REVIEWER_MODEL, with
#   fallback to gpt-5.4-mini when REVIEWER_MODEL is a `-codex`
#   variant — those models 400 on ChatGPT OAuth, so they can't be
#   used for the refresh ping itself).
# YUKTICASTLE_CODEX_REFRESH_MODEL=gpt-5.4-mini
#
# YUKTICASTLE_CODEX_REFRESH_TIMEOUT_MS (default: 20000 = 20s)
#   Subprocess timeout for the `codex exec` refresh invocation.
#   Bump if your network/host is slow.
# YUKTICASTLE_CODEX_REFRESH_TIMEOUT_MS=20000

# Optional: OpenRouter — used by `npm run agents:ask` (one-shot
# prompts) and the future role DAG (ENHANCEMENTS.md #15) for
# tool-free roles. Free models work without a top-up; paid models
# require credit on the OpenRouter account. Get a key:
# https://openrouter.ai/keys
OPENROUTER_API_KEY=

# Optional: default OpenRouter model for `agents:ask`. Leave unset
# to use the free Llama 3.3 70b (meta-llama/llama-3.3-70b-instruct:free).
# Examples:
#   YUKTICASTLE_OPENROUTER_MODEL=google/gemini-2.0-flash-exp:free
#   YUKTICASTLE_OPENROUTER_MODEL=deepseek/deepseek-r1:free   # reasoning-heavy
#   YUKTICASTLE_OPENROUTER_MODEL=anthropic/claude-3.5-sonnet # paid passthrough
# YUKTICASTLE_OPENROUTER_MODEL=

# Optional: sandbox setup timeouts (milliseconds).
#
# YUKTICASTLE_NPM_INSTALL_TIMEOUT_MS — caps the in-container
#   `npm install --no-audit --no-fund` hook. Default 120000 (120s)
#   covers cold-cache installs on most repos. Bump to 180000 or
#   higher for monorepos with heavy dep trees (gextrader, large
#   Next.js + Prisma stacks, etc.). The library hard-defaulted to
#   60s before this knob existed — that's what bit Phase E0 on
#   gextrader and is why this knob exists. Symptom: `HookTimeoutError:
#   Hook 'npm install --no-audit --no-fund' timed out after Xms`
#   before "Agent started" ever logs.
# YUKTICASTLE_NPM_INSTALL_TIMEOUT_MS=180000
#
# YUKTICASTLE_COPY_TIMEOUT_MS — caps the host→container worktree
#   copy. Default 240000 (240s).
# YUKTICASTLE_COPY_TIMEOUT_MS=300000

# ─── Security Auditor (PR F, opt-in) ───
#
# When enabled, a third phase runs after the reviewer: an independent
# codex-based agent (gpt-5) audits the diff for security concerns and
# writes a findings report to .yukticastle/security-findings/<branch>.md.
# The auditor is AUDIT-ONLY — it never modifies source code, just
# produces the findings file as a single audit commit.
#
# Halt behavior: if the auditor finds any `critical` findings, the run
# is marked `security_halt` and the auto-PR flow is suppressed. Operator
# must inspect findings before merging anything. Output:
#   git show <branch>:.yukticastle/security-findings/<branch>.md
#
# Cost: one additional codex run (~$0 on ChatGPT Team OAuth via PR #48,
# or ~$0.05–0.20 on OPENAI_API_KEY paid path for a typical diff).
#
# Wall-time: ~0 added (PR G parallelizes auditor with reviewer — both
# run concurrently in their own sandcastle containers; total wall-time
# is max(reviewer, auditor) instead of reviewer + auditor). Operator
# may see interleaved log output from both phases during the run.
#
# YUKTICASTLE_SECURITY_AUDITOR=true

# ─── Migration Auditor (PR H, opt-in + diff-gated) ───
#
# Dual-gated role: env flag PLUS the diff must touch a migration
# path. Catches data-loss patterns BEFORE they merge:
#   - DROP TABLE without backfill
#   - DROP COLUMN without code-side deprecation
#   - ALTER COLUMN ... NOT NULL without populating existing rows
#   - Type changes that may not cast cleanly
#   - Removed FK constraints relied on for referential integrity
#
# Runs in the same parallel group as the reviewer + security_auditor
# (when both auditors enabled, total wall-time = max of the three,
# not the sum — PR G's parallel-group execution).
#
# Halt behavior: critical findings emit `migration_halt`, which
# OUTRANKS `security_halt` in the severity priority because data
# loss is irreversible. Auto-PR suppressed; operator inspects
#   git show <branch>:.yukticastle/migration-findings/<branch>.md
#
# YUKTICASTLE_MIGRATION_AUDITOR=true
#
# Path patterns that trigger the auditor (comma-list). Default
# covers Prisma + generic + Rails + Drizzle + raw SQL. Extension
# patterns (*.ext) match by suffix; everything else is a prefix
# match against the changed file's path.
# YUKTICASTLE_MIGRATION_PATHS=prisma/migrations/,migrations/,db/migrate/,drizzle/,*.sql

# ─── Architect / Planner (PR I, opt-in pre-implementer) ───
#
# When enabled, an architect phase runs BEFORE the implementer and
# produces a structured plan at `.yukticastle/plans/<branch>.md`
# covering: files to create/modify, sequencing, risks, out-of-scope,
# acceptance criteria.
#
# The implementer's prompt template includes a {{PLAN}} section that
# substitutes the plan content. When architect is gated off, {{PLAN}}
# expands to empty — implementer behaves identically to pre-PR-I.
#
# Cost: one extra claude-opus run before the implementer (~$0 on
# MAX-OAuth; ~$0.10-0.20 on API key for a typical plan).
# Wall-time: adds ~2-4 minutes — architect runs SEQUENTIALLY before
# implementer; there's no parallel option since implementer consumes
# its output.
#
# Failure mode is forgiving: if architect crashes, run continues to
# implementer with empty {{PLAN}}. runs.jsonl records
# `runState.result = "architect_crashed"`.
#
# When to enable:
#   - Tasks larger than ~5 files or ~300 LOC (rough heuristic)
#   - Tasks where the right decomposition is non-obvious
#   - Cross-cutting changes spanning multiple layers
# When to skip:
#   - Small tasks; implementer can figure it out
#   - Tight-budget runs
#
# YUKTICASTLE_ARCHITECT=true

# ─── Test Engineer (PR J, opt-in post-implementer) ───
#
# When enabled, a Test Engineer phase runs in parallel with the
# reviewer + auditors after the implementer. Reads the implementer's
# diff, identifies code paths without tests, writes tests, commits
# them as a single "test: coverage for <branch>" commit.
#
# Different from auditors in two ways:
#   1. Writes CODE (test files committed to branch), not findings
#      markdown.
#   2. NO halt path. Test gaps are forgivable — operator can request
#      more coverage in code review.
#
# Default model: claude-sonnet-4-6 (writing tests is closer to
# implementation than to planning; Sonnet is the sweet spot for
# pattern-following code).
#
# Cost: one extra claude-sonnet run per YC run when enabled.
# ~$0 on MAX-OAuth; ~$0.05-0.15 on API key.
# Wall-time: ~0 added — runs concurrently with reviewer + auditors
# (PR #56's parallel-group execution). Total wall-time stays at
# max(reviewer, auditor, test_engineer).
#
# Failure mode: forgiving. Crash → runState.result =
# "test_engineer_crashed", run still completes normally.
#
# When to enable:
#   - New feature work where coverage matters (greenfield modules)
#   - Bug fixes (regression coverage is high-leverage)
# When to skip:
#   - Refactors (existing tests should already cover the behavior)
#   - Trivial tasks where coverage isn't a concern
#   - Operator prefers writing tests by hand
#
# YUKTICASTLE_TEST_ENGINEER=true
